<H3> <TI>   Vice Premier Zou Jiahua Continues U.S. Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Vice Premier Zou Jiahua Continues U.S. Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Meets U.S. Acting Secretary of State </H4>

<F P=102> OW0305180194 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 1652 
GMT 3 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW0305180194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Chinese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By reporter Wang Jinhe (3769 6855 0735)] </F>
  [Text] Washington, 3 May (XINHUA) -- U.S. Acting Secretary 
of State Talbott met with visiting Chinese Vice Premier Zou 
Jiahua at the State Department on the morning of 3 May. 
  At the meeting, Talbott extended a welcome and greetings 
from 
U.S. Secretary of State Christopher to Zou Jiahua. The 
secretary of state has been on a tour of the Middle East. The 
Chinese vice premier in turn asked Talbott to convey his 
gratitude and regards to Christopher. 
  Talbott said: President Clinton's meeting with the vice 
premier yesterday has a positive significance for promoting the 
improvement and development of U.S.-Chinese relations. The U.S. 
Government has steadfastly observed the principles laid down in 
the three U.S.-Chinese joint communiques and has implemented the 
"One China" policy. The two sides have reached a common 
understanding on the importance of U.S.-Chinese relations. 
  He also emphatically pointed out that in its policy toward 
China, the United States has adhered to the principles of 
respecting sovereignty and of mutually beneficial cooperation, 
adding that Washington is pleased to see the determination shown 
by both sides to eliminate existing differences between the two 
countries to facilitate the steady development of U.S.-Chinese 
relations. 
  After the meeting, Zou Jiahua said: China has all along 
attached great importance to maintaining and developing 
relations with the United States. We are sincere in our 
attitude toward solving problems between the two countries, and 
have exerted and will continue to exert great efforts to this 
end. We hope that the United States will have the same attitude 
and take positive action to facilitate the normalization of 
relations between the two countries at an early date. 

</TEXT>

