<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yangtze Valley Produces 43% of Nation's Steel </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yangtze Valley Produces 43% of Nation's Steel </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0405010994 Beijing XINHUA in English 0033 GMT 4 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0405010994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Wuhan, May 4 (XINHUA) -- The annual steel output of 
the Chang Jiang river valley last year reached 35 million tons, 
accounting for 43 percent of China's total, according to 
authoritative statistics. 
  At present, six out of the country's 13 most profitable iron 
and steel enterprises are in the Chang Jiang valley. They 
include the Baoshan Steel Works Group in Shanghai at the mouth 
of the Yangtze, and Maanshan, Wuhan and Panzhihua iron and steel 
companies on the lower, middle and upper reaches of the river. 
  The Baoshan Steel Works Group is now the country's most 
advanced steel enterprise involving the biggest amount of 
foreign investment. Last year, the group gained four billion 
yuan (460 million U.S. dollars) of pre-tax profits, ranking 
first among all iron and steel enterprises in China. 
  The Wuhan Iron and Steel Company's annual output of iron and 
of steel both surpassed five million tons for the first time 
last year, at 5.4 million tons and 5.224 million tons 
respectively. 
  Experts noted that the growth of the iron and steel industry 
in the Chang Jiang valley has helped promote economic 
development in the whole area, contribute greatly to the opening 
up and development of the Pudong new area in Shanghai and will 
supply needed rolled steel and other materials for the 
construction of the Three Gorges hydraulic projects on the 
Yangtze. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

