<F P=100> NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   NPC To Adopt Measure Against Copyright Violations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    NPC To Adopt Measure Against Copyright Violations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0305140694 Beijing XINHUA in English 1358 GMT 3 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0305140694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, May 3 (XINHUA) -- The Standing Committee of 
the National People's Congress (NPC), China's legislature, is 
expected to formulate a decision on punishing criminals who 
violate copyrights at the committee's seventh session which 
opens May 5. 
  Spokesman of the General Office of the NPC Standing 
Committee 
Shen Zhangrong said this morning that China's Copyright Law has 
played a "significant role" in protecting copyrights and 
promoting the development of China's cultural and scientific 
causes since it was put into effect on June 1, 1991. 
  "However, piracy of books, audio and video tapes, and 
computer software has become quite rampant in recent years, in 
illegal attempts to reap huge profits," Shen said. 
  This has infringed upon the rights of the authors and 
destroyed the normal order of the socialist cultural market and 
economic activities. "It has also affected foreign trade of the 
country and its cultural and scientific exchanges and 
cooperation with foreign countries," said the spokesman, adding 
that perpetrators of this kind of activity should be severely 
punished. 
  During the eight-day session, the legislators will also 
deliberate over nine other draft laws and regulations. They are 
the draft law on management of urban real estate, draft 
supplementary provisions to regulations governing offenses 
against public order, draft amendments to the regulations on 
active service and ranks of military officers of the People's 
Liberation Army, the draft law on judges and the draft law on 
prosecutors. 
  The legislators will also hear a report on the construction 
of the Three-Gorges Dam project. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

