<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Taipei Seeks To Become Nonregional IDB Member </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Taipei Seeks To Become Nonregional IDB Member </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0405075894 Taipei CNA in English 0715 GMT 4 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0405075894 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Y.C. Tsai] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, May 4 (CNA) -- Governor Samuel Shieh of the 
Central Bank of China said Wednesday [4 May] that he would seek 
the support of Latin American countries for Taiwan's bid to 
become a non-regional member of the Inter-American Development 
Bank (IDB). 
  Shieh made the remark prior to his departure for Managua, 
Nicaragua with President Li Teng-hui, who embarked on a 13-day 
official visit to Nicaragua, Costa Rica, South Africa, and 
Swaziland Wednesday morning. 
  To help promote Taiwan's efforts to become an IDB member, 
Shieh said, the Ministry of Finance has earmarked NT [new 
Taiwan] $135 million (US$5.09 million) in its 1995 fiscal year 
budget as a trust fund for the Inter-American Bank. 
  In addition, he pointed out, the Export-Import Bank of the 
Republic of China [ROC] has decided to join with the IDB to 
extend a soft loan of US$50 million to Nicaragua, of which the 
Export- Import Bank will provide US$30 million. 
  Founded in 1959, the IDB boasts 19 members and is the 
world's 
largest regional development bank. The bank, with its 
headquarters in Washington, D.C., offers medium and long-term 
loans to Latin American countries to help boost their economic 
development. 

</TEXT>

