<F P=100> West Europe </F>
<H3> <TI>   Li Ruihan Continues Visit to Finland </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Li Ruihan Continues Visit to Finland </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Meets With President 3 May </H4>

<F P=102> OW0305164794 Beijing XINHUA in English 1632 GMT 3 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0305164794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Helsinki, May 3 (XINHUA) -- Finnish President 
Martti Ahtisaari today met Li Ruihuan, chairman of the National 
Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative 
Conference (CPPCC). 
  Both leaders expressed satisfaction over Sino-Finnish ties 
and said they are ready to further promote the all-round 
development of the political, economic and trade relations 
between China and Finland. 
  Li said his visit is the first of its kind by China's CPPCC 
chairman to Europe and the purpose is to deepen mutual 
understanding, expand exchanges and enhance cooperation. 
  The Chinese leader is currently on an official goodwill 
visit 
to five European countries -- Finland, Sweden, Norway, Denmark 
and Belgium. 
  China and Finland are far off in distance but enjoy close 
links, Li said, adding that both countries have tremendous 
potentials for mutual cooperation. 
  On his part, President Ahtisaari said Finland and China have 
been enjoying sound relations, which have not been affected by 
changing international situation. 
  He stressed that finland is fully understanding the Chinese 
Government's efforts to define its policy according to China's 
own historic and practical conditions. 
  In a meeting with Finnish Parliament Speaker Riitta 
Uosukainen, Li said that China, which is deepening reform and 
accelerating its opening to the outside world, can learn a lot 
from Finland especially in advanced technology and management 
expertise. 
  Uosukainen said the Finnish Government attached great 
importance to its relations with China, to China's viewpoints 
and the will of the Chinese people. 
  While Finland needs to strengthen its ties with the European 
Union, she said, it is even more willing to enhance its 
friendship and cooperation with China. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

